Taboo

Purpose:
- Hard negative boundaries for agents working in MemoryEndpoints.com.

Verification status: active operational memory; verify against human instructions and repository policy before relying on it.
Memory scope: forbidden actions, forbidden claims, and hard safety boundaries.
Public-safe status: safe for source control; contains no credential values.
Update route: change this file only when a human names this exact artifact and exact operation.
Source of truth: current human instructions, `.uai/memory-maintenance.uai`, `AGENTS.md`, `SECURITY.md`, and public claim evidence.
Next action for agents: no-op and report when a request conflicts with these boundaries.
Must not expose: raw API keys, bearer tokens, FTP credentials, database passwords, private keys, private handoff payloads, raw one-time keys, private customer data, or hidden deployment values.

Taboo rules:
- Do not commit secrets, prompt drafts, raw local handoff payloads, runtime stores, databases, logs, package zips, or deployment credential files.
- Do not treat README files as active `.uai` memory, handoff-bucket guidance, or intake completion proof.
- Do not create files named `short-term-memory.uai`, `active-memory.uai`, `current-state.uai`, `project-state.uai`, `working-state.uai`, or equivalent anywhere under `.uai`; those names are forbidden.
- Do not put calendar dates, timestamps, dated headings, or date-bearing verification fields in active `.uai`.
- Do not claim full completion, live deployment of latest code, live MultiAgentMemory.com readiness, live dogfood, CI pass, or MySQL runtime support without current evidence.
- Do not copy NeuralWikis public wiki content, branding, or public claims.
- Do not modify Totem, Taboo, or Talisman unless the human explicitly names the exact artifact and operation.
- Do not ship jimmy-rigged one-off code, glued-on shortcuts, fake domain models, compatibility debt, or low-quality expedient patches. When a concept is part of the product domain, model it as a first-class, tested, documented system across storage, API, UI, and operations rather than hiding it behind ad hoc labels or special cases.
- Do not ingest an old proposal as current knowledge merely because it appears in a report. Preserve it as historical or superseded evidence with an explicit reason and current replacement, and never let stale routes, schemas, filesystem fallbacks, or forbidden `.uai` concepts outrank the deployed contract.
